data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has four thread-abort patterns that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `ProcessLoop()` while loop | `CancellationToken` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | catch block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `OperationCanceledException` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Keeps thread alive after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `GetNextItem()` "may block" + `Thread.Sleep` | `token.WaitHandle` / async alternatives |

### Key Pitfalls in This Code

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8** ŌĆö the `Stop()` method will crash.
2. **`GetNextItem()` may block** ŌĆö even after setting `_running = false`, the thread could be stuck indefinitely. Cooperative cancellation requires passing a `CancellationToken` into that blocking call.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` allowed the loop to continue** ŌĆö in the new model, you catch `OperationCanceledException` at the loop level and decide whether to continue or exit.
4. **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` is not cancellable** ŌĆö replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` or `Join(timeout)`.
5. **`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`** ŌĆö you must dispose it to avoid timer/callback leaks.

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;

        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted.
                // If GetNextItem blocks on a ManualResetEvent, replace
                // event.WaitOne() with:
                //   WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle });
                // If it blocks on I/O, switch to async overloads that
                // accept a CancellationToken.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces the ThreadAbortException catch block.
                // Clean up partial work exactly as before.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();

                // Unlike Thread.ResetAbort, we simply break out of the
                // loop. If you need to continue processing remaining
                // items, replace 'break' with 'continue' and create a
                // new CancellationTokenSource per work-item instead.
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts == null || _workerThread == null)
            return;

        // Signal cooperative cancellation (replaces _running = false + Thread.Abort)
        _cts.Cancel();

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time. With cooperative cancellation this
            // means GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
            // Log a warning ŌĆö there is no safe forced-kill equivalent in
            // modern .NET. If the work is truly uncooperative, move it
            // to a child process and use Process.Kill().
            Console.Error.WriteLine(
                "Warning: worker thread did not exit within 2 seconds.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O) ŌĆö a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown in .NET 8; the `when` filter avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` (or `continue`) | No abort to reset ŌĆö you decide whether to exit or continue |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forced injection |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping and hoping |
| ŌĆö | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed to avoid leaks |

### Critical: You Must Update `GetNextItem`

The biggest pitfall is that **`GetNextItem()` "may block"**. If it doesn't accept and check a `CancellationToken`, the thread will hang even after `Cancel()` is called. Example fix:

```csharp
// BEFORE: blocks indefinitely, no way to interrupt
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// AFTER: wakes up when cancellation is requested
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses a `ManualResetEvent`:
```csharp
// Replace event.WaitOne() with:
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```
